{"id":"seed:en:sun","source":"seed:en:sun","license":"CC0-1.0","attribution":"The Primer seed corpus","text":"The Sun is the star at the centre of our solar system. It is a giant ball of very hot gas, mostly hydrogen and helium, held together by its own gravity. Deep inside the Sun, the pressure is so great and the temperature so high — about 15 million degrees Celsius — that hydrogen atoms squash together to make helium. This process is called nuclear fusion, and it releases enormous amounts of energy. The energy travels outward through the Sun for hundreds of thousands of years before reaching the surface, and from there it shines into space as light and heat.\n\nThe Sun is much bigger than the Earth. About 1.3 million Earths could fit inside it. Even though it looks small in the sky, the Sun is so far away — about 150 million kilometres — that its light takes around eight minutes to reach us. When you look at the sunset, you are seeing light that left the Sun eight minutes earlier.\n\nThe Sun is the reason life on Earth is possible. Plants use sunlight to make their food in a process called photosynthesis. Animals (including us) eat the plants, or eat other animals that ate plants, so almost every living thing on Earth depends on the Sun's energy. The Sun also drives the weather: it heats the air and the oceans, which makes wind, clouds, and rain.\n\nLike all stars, the Sun has a life cycle. It formed about 4.6 billion years ago from a cloud of gas and dust, and it has enough hydrogen left to keep shining for about another 5 billion years. Eventually it will swell up into a kind of star called a red giant, then shed its outer layers and become a small, dense remnant called a white dwarf. That is a long time away — far longer than humans have existed.","topics":["space","sun","stars","fusion","solar system"]}
{"id":"seed:en:moon","source":"seed:en:moon","license":"CC0-1.0","attribution":"The Primer seed corpus","text":"The Moon is Earth's only natural satellite — a round, rocky world that orbits Earth once every 27 days or so. It is about a quarter of Earth's diameter, which makes it unusually large compared to its planet. The Moon has no air to breathe and almost no water on its surface, so the sky there is always black, even during the day, and the ground is covered in fine grey dust and craters left by ancient impacts.\n\nThe Moon does not make its own light. What we see when the Moon shines is sunlight bouncing off its surface. Because the Moon orbits Earth and Earth orbits the Sun, the part of the Moon that we can see lit up changes over the month. This is why the Moon goes through phases: a thin crescent grows into a half, then a fuller shape, then a full Moon, and then shrinks back the other way. A full cycle of phases takes about 29.5 days.\n\nThe Moon always shows us the same face. This is because it spins on its own axis at exactly the same rate that it orbits Earth — a coincidence that is actually caused by Earth's gravity slowly tugging on the Moon over billions of years. The far side of the Moon was a complete mystery to humans until spacecraft photographed it in 1959.\n\nThe Moon's gravity also pulls on Earth's oceans, which is the main reason we have tides. Twice each day in most places, the sea level rises and falls because the water is being tugged toward the Moon.\n\nMost scientists think the Moon formed about 4.5 billion years ago when a Mars-sized object crashed into the young Earth. The debris from that collision came together in orbit and slowly clumped into the Moon we know today. Twelve people have walked on the Moon, all between 1969 and 1972, during the Apollo missions.","topics":["space","moon","tides","phases","apollo"]}
{"id":"seed:en:earth-orbit-day-night","source":"seed:en:earth-orbit-day-night","license":"CC0-1.0","attribution":"The Primer seed corpus","text":"Day and night happen because the Earth spins. Earth turns all the way around its own axis once every 24 hours, like a slowly spinning top. The half of the Earth that is facing the Sun is having day; the half facing away is having night. As the planet keeps turning, the day side rolls into night, and the night side rolls into day. This is why the Sun seems to rise in the east and set in the west — it is really the ground beneath your feet that is moving, not the Sun.\n\nAt the same time as it spins, Earth is also travelling around the Sun. One full trip around the Sun takes one year, or about 365.25 days. The extra quarter day is why we add an extra day to February every four years (a leap year).\n\nEarth's spinning axis is not straight up and down compared to its orbit; it is tilted by about 23.5 degrees. This tilt is what gives us seasons. When the part of Earth where you live is tilted toward the Sun, the Sun appears higher in the sky and the days are longer and warmer — that is summer. Six months later, your part of Earth is tilted away from the Sun, the Sun is lower, the days are shorter, and it is colder — that is winter. Spring and autumn are the in-between times.\n\nThe Northern Hemisphere and the Southern Hemisphere have opposite seasons because when one is tilted toward the Sun, the other is tilted away. So when it is summer in Australia, it is winter in Canada.\n\nEarth's spinning is what gives wind storms their swirl, what makes a free-falling object curve sideways slightly, and what stops the planet's atmosphere from settling on one side. Without the spin, one half of Earth would be permanently scorching and the other permanently frozen.","topics":["space","earth","day","night","seasons"]}
{"id":"seed:en:planets-solar-system","source":"seed:en:planets-solar-system","license":"CC0-1.0","attribution":"The Primer seed corpus","text":"Our solar system has eight planets that orbit the Sun. In order from nearest to farthest, they are Mercury, Venus, Earth, Mars, Jupiter, Saturn, Uranus, and Neptune. The first four are called the rocky planets or terrestrial planets, because they have solid surfaces made mostly of rock and metal. The last four are the gas giants and ice giants — much bigger worlds made mostly of gas and liquid, with no solid surface to stand on.\n\nMercury is the smallest planet and the closest to the Sun. It has almost no atmosphere, which means its days are scorching and its nights are freezing. Venus is about the same size as Earth, but its thick clouds trap heat so well that it is actually the hottest planet — even hotter than Mercury, with a surface hot enough to melt lead.\n\nEarth is the only planet we know of with liquid water on its surface and life. Mars, the next planet out, is sometimes called the Red Planet because of the rusty iron in its dust. Mars has tall volcanoes, deep canyons, and signs that water once flowed there long ago.\n\nJupiter is by far the biggest planet — more than 300 times the mass of Earth. It has a famous storm called the Great Red Spot that has been swirling for at least 350 years. Saturn is famous for its bright rings, which are made of countless chunks of ice and rock orbiting the planet. All four giant planets have rings, but Saturn's are the brightest.\n\nUranus and Neptune are far out at the edge of the solar system, where the Sun is just a very bright star. They are extremely cold and have winds faster than the worst storms on Earth. Uranus is unusual because it spins on its side.\n\nBeyond Neptune are dwarf planets like Pluto, plus countless smaller icy bodies in a region called the Kuiper Belt.","topics":["space","planets","solar system","mercury","venus","mars","jupiter","saturn","uranus","neptune"]}
{"id":"seed:en:stars","source":"seed:en:stars","license":"CC0-1.0","attribution":"The Primer seed corpus","text":"Stars are giant balls of glowing gas, mostly hydrogen and helium. They form when a cloud of gas and dust in space slowly collapses under its own gravity. As the cloud squeezes together, it gets hotter and hotter. When the centre becomes hot enough — millions of degrees — hydrogen atoms start fusing together to make helium, releasing huge amounts of energy. That energy is what makes a star shine.\n\nThe Sun is a star, and it is the closest one to us. It looks much bigger and brighter than other stars only because it is so much closer. The next nearest star, Proxima Centauri, is more than 250,000 times farther away than the Sun. Even at the speed of light, its light takes more than four years to reach Earth.\n\nStars come in different sizes and colours. Cool stars are red, warmer stars are yellow or white, and the hottest stars are blue. The Sun is a yellow-white star of medium size and middle age. Some stars are tiny — only the size of a city — but extremely dense and made of leftover material from a star that exploded. Others are so big that if you put one where the Sun is, it would swallow up Earth and even Jupiter.\n\nStars do not last forever. They live by burning hydrogen, and when they run out of fuel, they change. Smaller stars like the Sun puff up into red giants, then shed their outer layers and end up as quiet white dwarfs. Very massive stars die more dramatically, exploding as supernovas. The explosion scatters the heavier elements the star made — carbon, oxygen, iron — into space, where they can become part of new stars and planets. The atoms in your body were made inside stars that lived and died long before the Sun was born.\n\nWhen you look up at a clear night sky, every twinkling point of light (except the planets) is a distant sun.","topics":["space","stars","fusion","supernova","stellar evolution"]}
{"id":"seed:en:galaxies-milky-way","source":"seed:en:galaxies-milky-way","license":"CC0-1.0","attribution":"The Primer seed corpus","text":"A galaxy is an enormous group of stars, gas, dust, and dark matter held together by gravity. A typical galaxy contains hundreds of billions of stars. Galaxies come in different shapes: some are flat spirals with curving arms, some are smooth oval blobs called ellipticals, and some are irregular and lumpy.\n\nOur Sun and all the stars you can see at night belong to a galaxy called the Milky Way. The Milky Way is a spiral galaxy, shaped a bit like a pinwheel with a bright bulge in the middle. From the inside, it looks to us like a faint band of milky light stretching across the night sky — which is how it got its name. The Sun is about two-thirds of the way out from the centre, on one of the spiral arms.\n\nThe Milky Way is huge. Light, which travels faster than anything else, takes about 100,000 years to cross from one side of it to the other. Even so, the Milky Way is just one of more than two trillion galaxies in the part of the universe we can see.\n\nGalaxies are not scattered evenly through space. They cluster together in groups, and the groups gather into bigger structures called superclusters. Between the galaxies are vast empty spaces called voids.\n\nMost galaxies, including ours, have a supermassive black hole at their centre. The one in the Milky Way is called Sagittarius A*. It is millions of times the mass of the Sun, but it sits very quietly compared to the noisy black holes in some other galaxies.\n\nGalaxies sometimes drift close enough that their gravity pulls them together. When two galaxies merge, the stars rarely actually collide because they are so far apart, but the shapes of the galaxies are stretched and reshaped over hundreds of millions of years. The Milky Way will eventually merge with our nearest large galactic neighbour, the Andromeda galaxy, in about four billion years.","topics":["space","galaxies","milky way","andromeda","universe"]}
{"id":"seed:en:black-holes","source":"seed:en:black-holes","license":"CC0-1.0","attribution":"The Primer seed corpus","text":"A black hole is a region of space where gravity is so strong that nothing — not even light — can escape from it once it gets close enough. That is why it is called black: no light comes out, so we cannot see it directly.\n\nBlack holes form when a very massive star runs out of fuel and collapses. The outer layers of the star are blasted away in a giant explosion called a supernova, while the core gets crushed inward by gravity. If the core is heavy enough, nothing can stop the collapse. All that matter ends up squashed into an unimaginably tiny point, and around that point is a sphere called the event horizon. The event horizon is the point of no return: anything that crosses it can never come back.\n\nFor anything outside the event horizon, a black hole is just a very strong source of gravity. If the Sun were magically replaced by a black hole of the same mass (which would be only a few kilometres across), the planets would keep orbiting just like before, because the gravity at our distance would be unchanged. We would freeze without sunlight, but Earth would not be sucked in.\n\nThere are two main sizes. Stellar-mass black holes are a few times the mass of the Sun and are the leftovers of dead massive stars. Supermassive black holes are millions or even billions of times the mass of the Sun and sit at the centres of galaxies. Astronomers think most galaxies have one.\n\nWe cannot see a black hole itself, but we can see what happens around it. Gas falling toward a black hole heats up to millions of degrees and glows brightly in X-rays before it disappears. In 2019, scientists released the first picture ever taken of the dark shadow of a black hole, surrounded by a glowing ring of hot gas.\n\nDespite their fearsome reputation, black holes are not cosmic vacuum cleaners. They only pull in things that get very close. Most of the universe is far too distant ever to fall into one.","topics":["space","black holes","gravity","supernova","event horizon"]}
{"id":"seed:en:comets-meteors","source":"seed:en:comets-meteors","license":"CC0-1.0","attribution":"The Primer seed corpus","text":"Comets and meteors are both small icy or rocky bits of the solar system, but they are not the same thing.\n\nA comet is a small body, usually only a few kilometres across, made of ice, dust, and frozen gases. Most comets spend their time far out in the cold edges of the solar system, where they stay frozen and dark. Sometimes a comet's orbit brings it close to the Sun. As it warms up, the ice turns to gas and dust streams out behind it, forming the comet's bright tail. The tail can be millions of kilometres long, but it is so thin you could almost see straight through it. A comet's tail always points away from the Sun, because the solar wind blows it like the wind blows a flag.\n\nFamous comets include Halley's Comet, which returns close to Earth roughly every 76 years and has been seen and recorded by people for at least two thousand years.\n\nMeteoroids are smaller — usually pieces of rock or metal, often no bigger than a grain of sand. Many of them are crumbs left behind by comets. When a meteoroid enters Earth's atmosphere, it slams into the air at very high speed, gets extremely hot, and glows as a streak of light across the sky. That streak is called a meteor or, in everyday language, a shooting star. Despite the name, it is not a star at all.\n\nMost meteoroids burn up completely in the atmosphere. A few are big enough that part of them survives the trip down and lands on the ground. Once a piece reaches the ground, we call it a meteorite. Some meteorites are pieces of asteroids, some are pieces of the Moon or Mars, blasted off by an ancient impact.\n\nWhen Earth passes through the dusty trail left by an old comet, you get a meteor shower: dozens of shooting stars per hour, all seeming to come from the same part of the sky. Famous meteor showers include the Perseids in August and the Geminids in December.","topics":["space","comets","meteors","meteor shower","halley"]}
{"id":"seed:en:eclipses","source":"seed:en:eclipses","license":"CC0-1.0","attribution":"The Primer seed corpus","text":"An eclipse happens when one object in space gets in the way of another and casts a shadow. From Earth, the two kinds we can see are solar eclipses and lunar eclipses.\n\nA solar eclipse happens when the Moon passes between the Sun and Earth, blocking out part or all of the Sun's light for a short time. During a total solar eclipse, the Moon perfectly covers the Sun's bright disc, the sky goes dark in the middle of the day, and the Sun's faint outer atmosphere — called the corona — becomes visible as a glowing ring. Total solar eclipses only last a few minutes, and you can only see them from a narrow strip of land where the Moon's shadow falls. Anywhere else, you might see a partial eclipse where only part of the Sun is covered.\n\nIt is dangerous to look directly at the Sun, even during an eclipse, because the unblocked parts are still extremely bright. People use special eclipse glasses or pinhole projectors to watch safely.\n\nA lunar eclipse happens the other way around. The Moon passes through the shadow of the Earth. Because Earth is much bigger than the Moon, the shadow lasts longer — a lunar eclipse can take more than an hour. During a total lunar eclipse, the Moon does not vanish; instead it turns a deep coppery red. This is because the only sunlight reaching the Moon at that point has bent through Earth's atmosphere, which filters out the blue colours and lets the red light through. It is the same reason sunsets are red. Some people call a totally eclipsed Moon a 'blood moon'.\n\nSolar eclipses can only happen at new moon, and lunar eclipses can only happen at full moon. They do not happen every month because the Moon's orbit is tilted slightly, so usually the Moon passes a little above or below the Sun's line.\n\nAncient peoples often found eclipses frightening. Today we can predict them centuries in advance.","topics":["space","eclipse","sun","moon","corona"]}
{"id":"seed:en:tides","source":"seed:en:tides","license":"CC0-1.0","attribution":"The Primer seed corpus","text":"Tides are the slow rise and fall of the sea level along coastlines. In most places, the sea rises and falls twice each day. The main reason this happens is the Moon's gravity.\n\nGravity pulls all objects with mass toward each other. The Moon pulls on Earth, and Earth pulls on the Moon. The Moon is too far away to lift the solid rock of Earth's surface much, but it can tug on the oceans, which flow easily. On the side of Earth facing the Moon, the water is pulled into a slight bulge. On the opposite side of Earth, there is a second bulge — caused by the fact that the solid Earth is being pulled toward the Moon a little more strongly than the water on the far side, leaving the far-side water behind. As Earth spins, different coastlines pass through these two bulges, so most places see two high tides and two low tides each day.\n\nThe Sun also pulls on Earth's oceans. The Sun is much bigger than the Moon, but it is also much farther away, so its tide-raising effect is about half as strong. When the Sun, Moon, and Earth line up — at full moon and new moon — the Sun's pull adds to the Moon's, and the tides are bigger than usual. These are called spring tides (the name has nothing to do with the season). When the Sun and Moon pull at right angles to each other — at first quarter and last quarter — the tides are smaller. These are called neap tides.\n\nThe size of the tide also depends on the shape of the coast. In a long narrow bay, water can pile up much higher than on an open shore. The Bay of Fundy in Canada has the biggest tides on Earth — the sea level there can change by more than 16 metres between low and high tide.\n\nTides matter for ships, fishermen, and animals like crabs and seabirds that live where the sea meets the land.","topics":["space","tides","moon","gravity","oceans"]}
{"id":"seed:en:big-bang","source":"seed:en:big-bang","license":"CC0-1.0","attribution":"The Primer seed corpus","text":"The Big Bang is the name for the beginning of the universe — the moment everything we can see started expanding from a hot, dense state about 13.8 billion years ago.\n\nThe name is a little misleading. The Big Bang was not an explosion in space, like a firework going off. It was the rapid expansion of space itself, everywhere all at once. There was no 'outside' for the early universe to expand into; space and time were both part of what was beginning.\n\nIn the very first moments, the universe was so hot and dense that ordinary atoms could not exist. As it expanded, it cooled. After a few minutes, simple atomic nuclei — hydrogen and helium — formed. Hundreds of thousands of years later, it had cooled enough for full atoms to form, and light could travel freely for the first time. That oldest light is still around today as a faint glow filling the whole sky in every direction. Astronomers call it the cosmic microwave background, and they study it carefully because it is like a baby picture of the universe.\n\nIt took hundreds of millions of years for gravity to pull the gas into the first stars and galaxies. Heavier elements like carbon, oxygen, and iron — the ones that make up planets and living bodies — were forged inside those stars and scattered when the stars exploded. Our Sun and Earth formed from the recycled remains of earlier generations of stars, about 4.6 billion years ago.\n\nThe universe is still expanding today. Astronomers can see this because galaxies that are far from us are moving away from us, and the more distant ones are moving away faster. To everyone's surprise, the expansion is also speeding up. The cause of this acceleration is mysterious; physicists call it dark energy and are still trying to understand what it is.\n\nThe Big Bang is the best explanation we have for why the universe looks the way it does. There are still many open questions, but the broad outline is supported by a lot of careful measurement.","topics":["space","universe","big bang","cosmology","dark energy"]}
